{
  "text": "We can express the range of eddy sizes present as a Reynolds number. This Reynolds number can be conventionally defined by 19) which is based on the assumption that h max = δ and h min = 100 following [CITATION_1] . By an analogous derivation to that given by [CITATION_2] , it can be shown that (5.18) can be re-expressed as 20) where k x is a constant defined such that the expected distance to the next closest eddy in the positive x direction will always be k x h if the height of the next closest eddy were known to be h. (More specifically, k x h represents the distance in a strip of height h to the nearest eddy of height between h and h + dh divided by h and dh.) The constant k y is its spanwise equivalent.",
